# Git Workflow

Never commit directly to `main`. All new edits go on a separate branch.

When asked to make changes and/or "commit & push":

1. Before editing (or before the first commit), create a feature branch off the
   latest `main`:
   - `git checkout main && git pull --ff-only`
   - `git checkout -b <type>/<short-topic>` (e.g. `feat/summary-view`, `fix/ios-zoom`)
2. Commit the work on that branch.
3. Push the branch: `git push -u origin HEAD`.
4. Open a PR into `main` with `gh pr create` (don't merge without being asked).

Only commit to `main` directly if the user explicitly says so for that task.

If changes were already made on `main` by mistake, ask before rewriting history;
prefer moving the work to a branch rather than force-pushing `main`.
